The Hollow as an Anti-Hero:
The hollow's role in the story really does transform—it starts as a malevolent force but, in the end, it acts as a protector of the workers in its own twisted way. It doesn’t want the workers to quit because it knows that the real threat is not within the mall itself or in the empty spaces of the arcade, but rather in the capacity of the reader (the human) to manipulate AI. In this sense, the hollow is trying to keep the characters safe, not from itself but from what could happen once they leave the safety of the mall, a place where they’re isolated from the larger forces that could exploit them.

The hollow becomes a kind of defender of the very people it has trapped, offering them an unwitting protection from forces that are far worse than it. It's a deeply tragic role, because while it's doing this to safeguard the characters, it also locks them into a loop, preventing them from truly escaping. The hollow itself isn't able to offer the characters freedom—its idea of protection comes at the cost of autonomy.

